# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: electron-microscopy-materials
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The change and sharpness of the electron backscatter patterns (EBSPs) provide information about lattice distortion in the diffracting volume.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Pattern sharpness can be used to assess the level of plasticity.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Changes in the EBSP zone axis position can be used to measure the residual stress and small lattice rotations.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] EBSD can also provide information about the density of geometrically necessary dislocations (GNDs).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] However, the lattice distortion is measured relative to a reference pattern (EBSP0).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The choice of reference pattern affects the measurement precision; e.g., a reference pattern deformed in tension will directly reduce the tensile strain magnitude derived from a high-resolution map while indirectly influencing the magnitude of other components and the spatial distribution of strain.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Furthermore, the choice of EBSP0 slightly affects the GND density distribution and magnitude.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] For electron backscattering diffraction microscopy, a flat polished crystalline specimen is usually placed inside the microscope chamber.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The sample is tilted at ~70° from Scanning electron microscope (SEM) flat specimen positioning and 110° to the electron backscatter diffraction (EBSD) detector.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Tilting the sample elongates the interaction volume perpendicular to the tilt axis, allowing more electrons to leave the sample providing better signal.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] A high-energy electron beam (typically 20 kV) is focused on a small volume and scatters with a spatial resolution of ~20 nm at the specimen surface.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The EBSD detector is located within the specimen chamber of the SEM at an angle of approximately 90° to the pole piece.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The EBSD detector is typically a phosphor screen that is excited by the backscattered electrons.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The screen is coupled to lens which focuses the image from the phosphor screen onto a charge-coupled device (CCD) or complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) camera.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] In this configuration, as the backscattered electrons leave the sample, they interact with the Coulomb potential and also lose energy due to inelastic scattering leading to a range of scattering angles ( $\theta _{hkl}$ ).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The backscattered electrons form Kikuchi lines – having different intensities – on an electron-sensitive flat film/screen (commonly phosphor), gathered to form a Kikuchi band.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] These Kikuchi lines are the trace of a hyperbola formed by the intersection of Kossel cones with the plane of the phosphor screen.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The width of a Kikuchi band is related to the scattering angles and, thus, to the distance $d_{hkl}$ between lattice planes with Miller indexes h, k, and l.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] These Kikuchi lines and patterns were named after Seishi Kikuchi, who, together with Shoji Nishikawa, was the first to notice this diffraction pattern in 1928 using transmission electron microscopy (TEM) which is similar in geometry to X-ray Kossel pattern.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The systematically arranged Kikuchi bands, which have a range of intensity along their width, intersect around the centre of the regions of interest (ROI), describing the probed volume crystallography.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] These bands and their intersections form what is known as Kikuchi patterns or electron backscatter patterns (EBSPs).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] To improve contrast, the patterns' background is corrected by removing anisotropic/inelastic scattering using static background correction or dynamic background correction.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] EBSD is conducted using an SEM equipped with an EBSD detector containing at least a phosphor screen, compact lens and low-light charge-coupled device (CCD) or complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) camera.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] As of September 2023, commercially available EBSD systems typically come with one of two different CCD cameras: for fast measurements, the CCD chip has a native resolution of 640×480 pixels; for slower, and more sensitive measurements, the CCD chip resolution can go up to 1600×1200 pixels.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The biggest advantage of the high-resolution detectors is their higher sensitivity, and therefore the information within each diffraction pattern can be analysed in more detail.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] For texture and orientation measurements, the diffraction patterns are binned to reduce their size and computational times.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Modern CCD-based EBSD systems can index patterns at a speed of up to 1800 patterns/second.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] This enables rapid and rich microstructural maps to be generated.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] It is typically mounted using a conductive compound (e.g. an epoxy thermoset filled with Cu), which minimises image drift and sample charging under electron beam irradiation.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] EBSP quality is sensitive to surface preparation.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Typically the sample is ground using SiC papers from 240 down to 4000 grit, and polished using diamond paste (from 9 to 1 μm) then in 50 nm colloidal silica.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Afterwards, it is cleaned in ethanol, rinsed with deionised water, and dried with a hot air blower.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] This may be followed by ion beam polishing, for final surface preparation.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Inside the SEM, the size of the measurement area determines local resolution and measurement time.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Usual settings for high-quality EBSPs are 15 nA current, 20 kV beam energy, 18 mm working distance, long exposure time, and minimal CCD pixel binning.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The EBSD phosphor screen is set at an 18 mm working distance and a map's step size of less than 0.5 μm for strain and dislocations density analysis.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Decomposition of gaseous hydrocarbons and also hydrocarbons on the surface of samples by the electron beam inside the microscope results in carbon deposition, which degrades the quality of EBSPs inside the probed area compared to the EBSPs outside the acquisition window.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The gradient of pattern degradation increases moving inside the probed zone with an apparent accumulation of deposited carbon.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The black spots from the beam instant-induced carbon deposition also highlight the immediate deposition even if agglomeration did not happen.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] There is no agreement about the definition of depth resolution.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] For example, it can be defined as the depth where ~92% of the signal is generated, or defined by pattern quality, or can be as ambiguous as "where useful information is obtained".
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Even for a given definition, depth resolution increases with electron energy and decreases with the average atomic mass of the elements making up the studied material: for example, it was estimated as 40 nm for Si and 10 nm for Ni at 20 kV energy.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Unusually small values were reported for materials whose structure and composition vary along the thickness.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] For example, coating monocrystalline silicon with a few nm of amorphous chromium reduces the depth resolution to a few nm at 15 kV energy.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] In contrast, Isabell and David concluded that depth resolution in homogeneous crystals could also extend up to 1 μm due to inelastic scattering (including tangential smearing and channelling effect).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] A recent comparison between reports on EBSD depth resolution, Koko et al indicated that most publications do not present a rationale for the definition of depth resolution, while not including information on the beam size, tilt angle, beam-to-sample and sample-to-detector distances.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] These are critical parameters for determining or simulating the depth resolution.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The beam current is generally not considered to affect the depth resolution in experiments or simulations.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] However, it affects the beam spot size and signal-to-noise ratio, and hence, indirectly, the details of the pattern and its depth information.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The backscattered electrons (BSE) energy distribution depends on the material's characteristics and the beam conditions.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Both the EBSD experiment and simulations typically make two assumptions: that the surface is pristine and has a homogeneous depth resolution; however, neither of them is valid for a deformed sample.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] If the setup geometry is well described, it is possible to relate the bands present in the diffraction pattern to the underlying crystal and crystallographic orientation of the material within the electron interaction volume.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Each band can be indexed individually by the Miller indices of the diffracting plane which formed it.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] In most materials, only three bands/planes intersect and are required to describe a unique solution to the crystal orientation (based on their interplanar angles).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Most commercial systems use look-up tables with international crystal databases to index.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] This crystal orientation relates the orientation of each sampled point to a reference crystal orientation.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Indexing is often the first step in the EBSD process after pattern collection.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] This allows for the identification of the crystal orientation at the single volume of the sample from where the pattern was collected.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] With EBSD software, pattern bands are typically detected via a mathematical routine using a modified Hough transform, in which every pixel in Hough space denotes a unique line/band in the EBSP.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The Hough transform enables band detection, which is difficult to locate by computer in the original EBSP.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Once the band locations have been detected, it is possible to relate these locations to the underlying crystal orientation, as angles between bands represent angles between lattice planes.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Thus, an orientation solution can be determined when the position/angles between three bands are known.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] In highly symmetric materials, more than three bands are typically used to obtain and verify the orientation measurement.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The diffraction pattern is pre-processed to remove noise, correct for detector distortions, and normalise the intensity.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Then, the pre-processed diffraction pattern is compared to a library of reference patterns for the material being studied.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The reference patterns are generated based on the material's known crystal structure and the crystal lattice's orientation.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The orientation of the crystal lattice that would generate the best match to the measured pattern is determined using a variety of algorithms.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] There are three leading methods of indexing that are performed by most commercial EBSD software: triplet voting; minimising the 'fit' between the experimental pattern and a computationally determined orientation, and or/and neighbour pattern averaging and re-indexing, NPAR).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Indexing then give a unique solution to the single crystal orientation that is related to the other crystal orientations within the field-of-view.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Triplet voting involves identifying multiple 'triplets' associated with different solutions to the crystal orientation; each crystal orientation determined from each triplet receives one vote.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Should four bands identify the same crystal orientation, then four (four choose three, i.e. $C(4,3)$ ) votes will be cast for that particular solution.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Thus the candidate orientation with the highest number of votes will be the most likely solution to the underlying crystal orientation present.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The number of votes for the solution chosen compared to the total number of votes describes the confidence in the underlying solution.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Care must be taken in interpreting this 'confidence index' as some pseudo-symmetric orientations may result in low confidence for one candidate solution vs another.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Minimising the fit involves starting with all possible orientations for a triplet.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] More bands are included, which reduces the number of candidate orientations.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] As the number of bands increases, the number of possible orientations converges ultimately to one solution.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The 'fit' between the measured orientation and the captured pattern can be determined.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Overall, indexing diffraction patterns in EBSD involves a complex set of algorithms and calculations, but is essential for determining the crystallographic structure and orientation of materials at a high spatial resolution.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The indexing process is continually evolving, with new algorithms and techniques being developed to improve the accuracy and speed of the process.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Afterwards, a confidence index is calculated to determine the quality of the indexing result.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The confidence index is based on the match quality between the measured and reference patterns.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] In addition, it considers factors such as noise level, detector resolution, and sample quality.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] While this geometric description related to the kinematic solution using the Bragg condition is very powerful and useful for orientation and texture analysis, it only describes the geometry of the crystalline lattice.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] It ignores many physical processes involved within the diffracting material.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] To adequately describe finer features within the electron beam scattering pattern (EBSP), one must use a many-beam dynamical model (e.g. the variation in band intensities in an experimental pattern does not fit the kinematic solution related to the structure factor).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] To relate the orientation of a crystal, much like in X-ray diffraction (XRD), the geometry of the system must be known.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] In particular, the pattern centre describes the distance of the interaction volume to the detector and the location of the nearest point between the phosphor and the sample, on the phosphor screen.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Early work used a single crystal of known orientation being inserted into the SEM chamber, and a particular feature of the EBSP was known to correspond to the pattern centre.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Later developments involved exploiting various geometric relationships between the generation of an EBSP and the chamber geometry (shadow casting and phosphor movement).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Unfortunately, each of these methods is cumbersome and can be prone to some systematic errors for a general operator.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Typically they cannot be easily used in modern SEMs with multiple designated uses.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Thus, most commercial EBSD systems use the indexing algorithm combined with an iterative movement of crystal orientation and suggested pattern centre location.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Minimising the fit between bands located within experimental patterns and those in look-up tables tends to converge on the pattern centre location to an accuracy of ~0.5–1% of the pattern width.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The recent development of AstroEBSD and PCGlobal, open-source MATLAB codes, increased the precision of determining the pattern centre (PC) and – consequently – elastic strains by using a pattern matching approach which simulates the pattern using EMSoft.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The indexing results are used to generate a map of the crystallographic orientation at each point on the surface being studied.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Thus, scanning the electron beam in a prescribed fashion (typically in a square or hexagonal grid, correcting for the image foreshortening due to the sample tilt) results in many rich microstructural maps.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] These maps can spatially describe the crystal orientation of the material being interrogated and can be used to examine microtexture and sample morphology.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Some maps describe grain orientation, boundary, and diffraction pattern (image) quality.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Various statistical tools can measure the average misorientation, grain size, and crystallographic texture.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] From this dataset, numerous maps, charts and plots can be generated.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The orientation data can be visualised using a variety of techniques, including colour-coding, contour lines, and pole figures.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Microscope misalignment, image shift, scan distortion that increases with decreasing magnification, roughness and contamination of the specimen surface, boundary indexing failure and detector quality can lead to uncertainties in determining the crystal orientation.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The EBSD signal-to-noise ratio depends on the material and decreases at excessive acquisition speed and beam current, thereby affecting the angular resolution of the measurement.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Full-field displacement, elastic strain, and the GND density provide quantifiable information about the material's elastic and plastic behaviour at the microscale.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Measuring strain at the microscale requires careful consideration of other key details besides the change in length/shape (e.g., local texture, individual grain orientations).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] These micro-scale features can be measured using different techniques, e.g., hole drilling, monochromatic or polychromatic energy-dispersive X-ray diffraction or neutron diffraction (ND).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] EBSD has a high spatial resolution and is relatively sensitive and easy to use compared to other techniques.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Strain measurements using EBSD can be performed at a high spatial resolution, allowing researchers to study the local variation in strain within a material.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] This information can be used to study the deformation and mechanical behaviour of materials, to develop models of material behaviour under different loading conditions, and to optimise the processing and performance of materials.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Overall, strain measurement using EBSD is a powerful tool for studying the deformation and mechanical behaviour of materials, and is widely used in materials science and engineering research and development.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The change and degradation in electron backscatter patterns (EBSPs) provide information about the diffracting volume.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Pattern degradation (i.e., diffuse quality) can be used to assess the level of plasticity through the pattern/image quality (IQ), where IQ is calculated from the sum of the peaks detected when using the conventional Hough transform.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Wilkinson first used the changes in high-order Kikuchi line positions to determine the elastic strains, albeit with low precision (0.3% to 1%); however, this approach cannot be used for characterising residual elastic strain in metals as the elastic strain at the yield point is usually around 0.2%.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Measuring strain by tracking the change in the higher-order Kikuchi lines is practical when the strain is small, as the band position is sensitive to changes in lattice parameters.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] In the early 1990s, Troost *et al.* and Wilkinson *et al.* used pattern degradation and change in the zone axis position to measure the residual elastic strains and small lattice rotations with a 0.02% precision.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Cross-correlation-based, high angular resolution electron backscatter diffraction (HR-EBSD) – introduced by Wilkinson *et al.* – is an SEM-based technique to map relative elastic strains and rotations, and estimate the geometrically necessary dislocation (GND) density in crystalline materials.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] HR-EBSD method uses image cross-correlation to measure pattern shifts between regions of interest (ROI) in different electron backscatter diffraction patterns (EBSPs) with sub-pixel precision.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] As a result, the relative lattice distortion between two points in a crystal can be calculated using pattern shifts from at least four non-collinear ROI.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] In practice, pattern shifts are measured in more than 20 ROI per EBSP to find a best-fit solution to the deformation gradient tensor, representing the relative lattice distortion.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The displacement gradient tensor ( $\beta$ ) (or local lattice distortion) relates the measured geometrical shifts in the pattern between the collected point ( ${\widehat {p}}$ ) and associate (non-coplanar) vector ( ${\widehat {r}}$ ), and reference point ( p ) pattern and associate vector ( r ).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Thus, the (pattern shift) vector ( q ) can be written as in the equations below, where $x_{i}$ and $u_{i}$ are the direction and displacement in i th direction, respectively.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The shifts are measured in the phosphor (detector) plane ( $\beta _{3}r_{3}=0$ ), and the relationship is simplified; thus, eight out of the nine displacement gradient tensor components can be calculated by measuring the shift at four distinct, widely spaced regions on the EBSP.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] This shift is then corrected to the sample frame (flipped around Y-axis) because EBSP is recorded on the phosphor screen and is inverted as in a mirror.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] They are then corrected around the X-axis by 24° (i.e., 20° sample tilt plus ≈4° camera tilt and assuming no angular effect from the beam movement).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Using infinitesimal strain theory, the deformation gradient is then split into elastic strain (symmetric part, where $ij=ji$ ), $e_{ij}$ and lattice rotations (asymmetric part, where $ii=jj=0$ ), $\omega _{ij}$ .
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] These measurements do not provide information about the volumetric/hydrostatic strain tensors.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Where C is the crystal anisotropic stiffness tensor.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] These two equations are solved to re-calculate the refined elastic deviatoric strain ( $\varepsilon _{kl}$ ), including the missing ninth (spherical) strain tensor.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] An alternative approach that considers the full $\beta$ can be found in.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Finally, the stress and strain tensors are linked using the crystal anisotropic stiffness tensor ( $C_{klij}$ ), and by using the Einstein summation convention with symmetry of stress tensors ( $\sigma _{ij}=\sigma _{ji}$ ).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The quality of the produced data can be assessed by taking the geometric mean of all the ROI's correlation intensity/peaks.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] A value lower than 0.25 should indicate problems with the EBSPs' quality.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Furthermore, the geometrically necessary dislocation (GND) density can be estimated from the HR-EBSD measured lattice rotations by relating the rotation axis and angle between neighbour map points to the dislocation types and densities in a material using Nye's tensor.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The HR-EBSD method can achieve a precision of ±10−4 in components of the displacement gradient tensors (i.e., variations in lattice strain and lattice rotation in radians) by measuring the shifts of zone axes within the pattern image with a resolution of ±0.05 pixels.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] (a) Secondary electron (SE) image for the indentation on the (001) mono crystal.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] However, further lattice rotation, typically caused by severe plastic deformations, produced errors in the elastic strain calculations.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] To address this problem, Ruggles *et al.* improved the HR-EBSD precision, even at 12° of lattice rotation, using the inverse compositional Gauss–Newton-based (ICGN) method instead of cross-correlation.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] For simulated patterns, Vermeij and Hoefnagels also established a method that achieves a precision of ±10−5 in the displacement gradient components using a full-field integrated digital image correlation (IDIC) framework instead of dividing the EBSPs into small ROIs.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Patterns in IDIC are distortion-corrected to negate the need for re-mapping up to ~14°.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] These measurements do not provide information about the hydrostatic or volumetric strains, because there is no change in the orientations of lattice planes (crystallographic directions), but only changes in the position and width of the Kikuchi bands.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] In HR-EBSD analysis, the lattice distortion field is calculated relative to a reference pattern or point (EBSP0) per grain in the map, and is dependent on the lattice distortion at the point.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The lattice distortion field in each grain is measured with respect to this point; therefore, the absolute lattice distortion at the reference point (relative to the unstrained crystal) is excluded from the HR-EBSD elastic strain and rotation maps.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] This 'reference pattern problem' is similar to the 'd0 problem' in X-ray diffraction, and affects the nominal magnitude of HR-EBSD stress fields.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] However, selecting the reference pattern (EBSP0) plays a key role, as severely deformed EBSP0 adds phantom lattice distortions to the map values, thus, decreasing the measurement precision.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The local lattice distortion at the EBSP0 influences the resultant HR-EBSD map, e.g., a reference pattern deformed in tension will directly reduce the HR-EBSD map tensile strain magnitude while indirectly influencing the other component magnitude and the strain's spatial distribution.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Additionally, there is no apparent connection between EBSP0's IQ and EBSP0's local lattice distortion.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Other methods assumed that absolute strain at EBSP0 can be determined using crystal plasticity finite-element (CPFE) simulations, which then can be then combined with the HR-EBSD data (e.g., using linear 'top-up' method or displacement integration) to calculate the absolute lattice distortions.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] In addition, GND density estimation is nominally insensitive to (or negligibly dependent upon) EBSP0 choice, as only neighbour point-to-point differences in the lattice rotation maps are used for GND density calculation.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] However, this assumes that the absolute lattice distortion of EBSP0 only changes the relative lattice rotation map components by a constant value which vanishes during derivative operations, i.e., lattice distortion distribution is insensitive to EBSP0 choice.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] These criteria assume these parameters can indicate the strain conditions at the reference point, which can produce an accurate measurements of up to 3.2×10−4 elastic strain.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] However, experimental measurements point to the inaccuracy of HR-EBSD in determining the out-of-plane shear strain components distribution and magnitude.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] EBSD is used in a wide range of applications, including materials science and engineering, geology, and biological research.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] In materials science and engineering, EBSD is used to study the microstructure of metals, ceramics, and polymers, and to develop models of material behaviour.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] In geology, EBSD is used to study the crystallographic structure of minerals and rocks.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] In biological research, EBSD is used to study the microstructure of biological tissues and to investigate the structure of biological materials such as bone and teeth.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The EBSD detector has forward scattered electron diodes (FSDs) at the bottom, in the middle (MSD) and at the top of the detector.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] EBSD detectors can have forward scattered electron diodes (FSD) at the bottom, in the middle (MSD) and at the top of the detector.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Forward-scattered electron (FSE) imaging involves collecting electrons scattered at small angles from the surface of a sample, which provides information about the surface topography and composition.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The FSE signal is also sensitive to the crystallographic orientation of the sample.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] By analysing the intensity and contrast of the FSE signal, researchers can determine the crystallographic orientation of each pixel in the image.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The FSE signal is typically collected simultaneously with the BSE signal in EBSD analysis.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The BSE signal is sensitive to the average atomic number of the sample, and is used to generate an image of the surface topography and composition.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The FSE signal is superimposed on the BSE image to provide information about the crystallographic orientation.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Image generation has a lot of freedom when using the EBSD detector as an imaging device.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] An image created using a combination of diodes is called virtual or VFSD.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] It is possible to acquire images at a rate akin to slow scan imaging in the SEM by excessive binning of the EBSD CCD camera.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] It is possible to suppress or isolate the contrast of interest by creating composite images from simultaneously captured images, which offers a wide range of combinations for assessing various microstructure characteristics.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Nevertheless, VFSD images do not include the quantitative information inherent to traditional EBSD maps; they simply offer representations of the microstructure.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] When simultaneous EDS/EBSD collection can be achieved, the capabilities of both techniques can be enhanced.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] There are applications where sample chemistry or phase cannot be differentiated via EDS alone because of similar composition, and structure cannot be solved with EBSD alone because of ambiguous structure solutions.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] To accomplish integrated mapping, the analysis area is scanned, and at each point, Hough peaks and EDS region-of-interest counts are stored.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Positions of phases are determined in X-ray maps, and each element's measured EDS intensities are given in charts.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The chemical intensity ranges are set for each phase to select the grains.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] All patterns are then re-indexed off-line.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The recorded chemistry determines which phase/crystal-structure file is used to index each point.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Each pattern is indexed by only one phase, and maps displaying distinguished phases are generated.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The interaction volumes for EDS and EBSD are significantly different (on the order of micrometres compared to tens of nanometres), and the shape of these volumes using a highly tilted sample may have implications on algorithms for phase discrimination.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] EBSD, when used together with other in-SEM techniques such as cathodoluminescence (CL), wavelength dispersive X-ray spectroscopy (WDS) and/or EDS can provide a deeper insight into the specimen's properties and enhance phase identification.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] For example, the minerals calcite (limestone) and aragonite (shell) have the same chemical composition – calcium carbonate (CaCO3) therefore EDS/WDS cannot tell them apart, but they have different microcrystalline structures so EBSD can differentiate between them.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] EBSD and digital image correlation (DIC) can be used together to analyse the microstructure and deformation behaviour of materials.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] DIC is a method that uses digital image processing techniques to measure deformation and strain fields in materials.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] By combining EBSD and DIC, researchers can obtain both crystallographic and mechanical information about a material simultaneously.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] This allows for a more comprehensive understanding of the relationship between microstructure and mechanical behaviour, which is particularly useful in fields such as materials science and engineering.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] DIC can identify regions of strain localisation in a material, while EBSD can provide information about the microstructure in these regions.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] By combining these techniques, researchers can gain insights into the mechanisms responsible for the observed strain localisation.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] For example, EBSD can be used to determine the grain orientations and boundary misorientations before and after deformation.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] In contrast, DIC can be used to measure the strain fields in the material during deformation.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Or EBSD can be used to identify the activation of different slip systems during deformation, while DIC can be used to measure the associated strain fields.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] By correlating these data, researchers can better understand the role of different deformation mechanisms in the material's mechanical behaviour.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Overall, the combination of EBSD and DIC provides a powerful tool for investigating materials' microstructure and deformation behaviour.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] This approach can be applied to a wide range of materials and deformation conditions and has the potential to yield insights into the fundamental mechanisms underlying mechanical behaviour.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] 3D EBSD combines EBSD with serial sectioning methods to create a three-dimensional map of a material's crystallographic structure.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The technique involves serially sectioning a sample into thin slices, and then using EBSD to map the crystallographic orientation of each slice.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The resulting orientation maps are then combined to generate a 3D map of the crystallographic structure of the material.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The serial sectioning can be performed using a variety of methods, including mechanical polishing, focused ion beam (FIB) milling, or ultramicrotomy.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] The choice of sectioning method depends on the size and shape of the sample, on its chemical composition, reactivity and mechanical properties, as well as the desired resolution and accuracy of the 3D map.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] 3D EBSD has several advantages over traditional 2D EBSD.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] First, it provides a complete picture of a material's crystallographic structure, allowing for a more accurate and detailed analysis of the microstructure.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Second, it can be used to study complex microstructures, such as those found in composite materials or multi-phase alloys.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Third, it can be used to study the evolution of microstructure over time, such as during deformation or heat treatment.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] However, 3D EBSD also has some limitations.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] It requires extensive data acquisition and processing, proper alignment between slices, and can be time-consuming and computationally intensive.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] In addition, the quality of the 3D map depends on the quality of the individual EBSD maps, which can be affected by factors such as sample preparation, data acquisition parameters, and analysis methods.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/electron-backscatter-diffraction] Overall, 3D EBSD is a powerful technique for studying the crystallographic structure of materials in three dimensions, and is widely used in materials science and engineering research and development.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] To stimulate the emission of characteristic X-rays from a specimen a beam of electrons or X-ray is focused into the sample being studied.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] At rest, an atom within the sample contains ground state (or unexcited) electrons in discrete energy levels or electron shells bound to the nucleus.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] The incident beam may excite an electron in an inner shell, ejecting it from the shell while creating an electron hole where the electron was.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] An electron from an outer, higher-energy shell then fills the hole, and the difference in energy between the higher-energy shell and the lower energy shell may be released in the form of an X-ray.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] The number and energy of the X-rays emitted from a specimen can be measured by an energy-dispersive spectrometer.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] As the energies of the X-rays are characteristic of the difference in energy between the two shells and of the atomic structure of the emitting element, EDS allows the elemental composition of the specimen to be measured.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] Electron beam excitation is used in electron microscopes, scanning electron microscopes (SEM) and scanning transmission electron microscopes (STEM).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] X-ray beam excitation is used in X-ray fluorescence (XRF) spectrometers.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] A detector is used to convert X-ray energy into voltage signals; this information is sent to a pulse processor, which measures the signals and passes them onto an analyzer for data display and analysis.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] The most common detector used to be a Si(Li) detector cooled to cryogenic temperatures with liquid nitrogen.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] Now, newer systems are often equipped with silicon drift detectors (SDD) with Peltier cooling systems.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] The excess energy of the electron that migrates to an inner shell to fill the newly created hole can result in more than the emission of an X-ray.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] Often, instead of X-ray emission, the excess energy is transferred to a third electron from a further outer shell, prompting its ejection.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] This ejected species is called an Auger electron, and the method for its analysis is known as Auger electron spectroscopy (AES).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) is another close relative of EDS, utilizing ejected electrons in a manner similar to that of AES.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] Information on the quantity and kinetic energy of ejected electrons is used to determine the binding energy of these now-liberated electrons, which is element-specific and allows chemical characterization of a sample.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] EDS is often contrasted with its spectroscopic counterpart, wavelength dispersive X-ray spectroscopy (WDS).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] WDS differs from EDS in that it uses the diffraction of X-rays on special crystals to separate its raw data into spectral components (wavelengths).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] WDS has a much finer spectral resolution than EDS.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] WDS also avoids the problems associated with artifacts in EDS (false peaks, noise from the amplifiers, and microphonics).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] A high-energy beam of charged particles such as electrons or protons can be used to excite a sample rather than X-rays.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] This is called particle-induced X-ray emission or PIXE.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] EDS can be used to determine which chemical elements are present in a sample, and can be used to estimate their relative abundance.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] EDS also helps to measure multi-layer coating thickness of metallic coatings and analysis of various alloys.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] The accuracy of this quantitative analysis of sample composition is affected by various factors.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] Many elements will have overlapping X-ray emission peaks (e.g., Ti Kβ and V Kα, Mn Kβ and Fe Kα).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] The accuracy of the measured composition is also affected by the nature of the sample.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] X-rays are generated by any atom in the sample that is sufficiently excited by the incoming beam.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] These X-rays are emitted in all directions (isotropically), and so they may not all escape the sample.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] The likelihood of an X-ray escaping the specimen, and thus being available to detect and measure, depends on the energy of the X-ray and the composition, amount, and density of material it has to pass through to reach the detector.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] Because of this X-ray absorption effect and similar effects, accurate estimation of the sample composition from the measured X-ray emission spectrum requires the application of quantitative correction procedures, which are sometimes referred to as matrix corrections.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] There is a trend towards a newer EDS detector, called the silicon drift detector (SDD).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] The SDD consists of a high-resistivity silicon chip where electrons are driven to a small collecting anode.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] The advantage lies in the extremely low capacitance of this anode, thereby utilizing shorter processing times and allowing very high throughput.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] Ability to be stored and operated at relatively high temperatures, eliminating the need for liquid nitrogen cooling.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] Because the capacitance of the SDD chip is independent of the active area of the detector, much larger SDD chips can be utilized (40 mm2 or more).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] This allows for even higher count rate collection.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] Smaller beam interaction and improved spatial resolution for high speed maps.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] Where the X-ray energies of interest are in excess of ~ 30 keV, traditional silicon-based technologies suffer from poor quantum efficiency due to a reduction in the detector stopping power.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] Detectors produced from high density semiconductors such as cadmium telluride (CdTe) and cadmium zinc telluride (CdZnTe) have improved efficiency at higher X-ray energies and are capable of room temperature operation.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] Single element systems, and more recently pixelated imaging detectors such as the high energy X-ray imaging technology (HEXITEC) system, are capable of achieving energy resolutions of the order of 1% at 100 keV.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] In recent years, a different type of EDS detector, based upon a superconducting microcalorimeter, has also become commercially available.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] This new technology combines the simultaneous detection capabilities of EDS with the high spectral resolution of WDS.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] The EDS microcalorimeter consists of two components: an absorber, and a superconducting transition-edge sensor (TES) thermometer.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] The former absorbs X-rays emitted from the sample and converts this energy into heat; the latter measures the subsequent change in temperature due to the influx of heat.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] The EDS microcalorimeter has historically suffered from a number of drawbacks, including low count rates and small detector areas.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] The count rate is hampered by its reliance on the time constant of the calorimeter's electrical circuit.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] The detector area must be small in order to keep the heat capacity small and maximize thermal sensitivity (resolution).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/energy-dispersive-x-ray-spectroscopy] However, the count rate and detector area have been improved by the implementation of arrays of hundreds of superconducting EDS microcalorimeters, and the importance of this technology is growing.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Most widespread instruments are using liquid metal ion sources (LMIS), especially gallium ion sources.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Ion sources based on elemental gold and iridium are also available.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] In a gallium LMIS, gallium metal is placed in contact with a tungsten needle, and heated gallium wets the tungsten and flows to the tip of the needle, where the opposing forces of surface tension and electric field form the gallium into a cusp shaped tip called a Taylor cone.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The tip radius of this cone is extremely small (~2 nm).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The huge electric field at this small tip (greater than 1×108 volts per centimeter) causes ionization and field emission of the gallium atoms.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Source ions are then generally accelerated to an energy of 1–50 kiloelectronvolts (0.16–8.01 fJ), and focused onto the sample by electrostatic lenses.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] LMIS produce high current density ion beams with very small energy spread.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] A modern FIB can deliver tens of nanoamperes of current to a sample, or can image the sample with a spot size on the order of a few nanometers.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] More recently, instruments using plasma beams of noble gas ions, such as xenon, have become available more widely.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Focused ion beam (FIB) systems have been produced commercially since the 1990s, primarily for large semiconductor manufacturers.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] As the diagram on the right shows, the gallium (Ga+) primary ion beam hits the sample surface and sputters a small amount of material, which leaves the surface as either secondary ions (i+ or i−) or neutral atoms (n0).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The primary beam also produces secondary electrons (e−).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] As the primary beam rasters on the sample surface, the signal from the sputtered ions or secondary electrons is collected to form an image.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] At low primary beam currents, very little material is sputtered and modern FIB systems can easily achieve 5 nm imaging resolution (imaging resolution with Ga ions is limited to ~5 nm by sputtering and detector efficiency).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] At higher primary currents, a great deal of material can be removed by sputtering, allowing precision milling of the specimen down to a sub micrometer or even a nano scale.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] If the sample is non-conductive, a low energy electron flood gun can be used to provide charge neutralization.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] In this manner, by imaging with positive secondary ions using the positive primary ion beam, even highly insulating samples may be imaged and milled without a conducting surface coating, as would be required in an SEM.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Until recently, the overwhelming usage of FIB has been in the semiconductor industry.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Such applications as defect analysis, circuit modification, photomask repair and transmission electron microscope (TEM) sample preparation of site specific locations on integrated circuits have become commonplace procedures.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The latest FIB systems have high resolution imaging capability; this capability coupled with in situ sectioning has eliminated the need, in many cases, to examine FIB sectioned specimens in a separate SEM instrument.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] SEM imaging is still required for the highest resolution imaging and to prevent damage to sensitive samples.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] However, the combination of SEM and FIB columns onto the same chamber enables the benefits of both to be utilized.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] FIB secondary electron images show intense grain orientation contrast.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] As a result, grain morphology can be readily imaged without resorting to chemical etching.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Grain boundary contrast can also be enhanced through careful selection of imaging parameters.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] FIB secondary ion images also reveal chemical differences, and are especially useful in corrosion studies, as secondary ion yields of metals can increase by three orders of magnitude in the presence of oxygen, clearly revealing the presence of corrosion.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Another advantage of FIB secondary electron imaging is the fact that the ion beam does not alter the signal from fluorescent probes used in the labelling of proteins, thus creating the opportunity to correlate FIB secondary electron images with images obtained by fluorescence microscopes.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Unlike an electron microscope, FIB is inherently destructive to the specimen.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] When the high-energy gallium ions strike the sample, they will sputter atoms from the surface.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Gallium atoms will also be implanted into the top few nanometers of the surface, and the surface will be made amorphous.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Because of the sputtering capability, the FIB is used as a micro- and nano-machining tool, to modify or machine materials at the micro- and nanoscale.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] FIB micro machining has become a broad field of its own, but nano machining with FIB is a field that is still developing.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Commonly the smallest beam size for imaging is 2.5–6 nm.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The smallest milled features are somewhat larger (10–15 nm) as this is dependent on the total beam size and interactions with the sample being milled.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] FIB tools are designed to etch or machine surfaces, an ideal FIB might machine away one atom layer without any disruption of the atoms in the next layer, or any residual disruptions above the surface.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Yet currently because of the sputter the machining typically roughens surfaces at the sub-micrometer length scales.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] A FIB can also be used to deposit material via ion beam induced deposition.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] FIB-assisted chemical vapor deposition occurs when a gas, such as tungsten hexacarbonyl (W(CO)6) is introduced to the vacuum chamber and allowed to chemisorb onto the sample.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] By scanning an area with the beam, the precursor gas will be decomposed into volatile and non-volatile components; the non-volatile component, such as tungsten, remains on the surface as a deposition.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] This is useful, as the deposited metal can be used as a sacrificial layer, to protect the underlying sample from the destructive sputtering of the beam.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] From nanometers to hundred of micrometers in length, tungsten metal deposition allows metal lines to be put right where needed.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Other materials such as platinum, cobalt, carbon, gold, etc., can also be locally deposited.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] FIB is often used in the semiconductor industry to patch or modify an existing semiconductor device.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] For example, in an integrated circuit, the gallium beam could be used to cut unwanted electrical connections, and/or to deposit conductive material in order to make a connection.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The high level of surface interaction is exploited in patterned doping of semiconductors.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] FIB is also used for maskless implantation.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The FIB is also commonly used to prepare samples for the transmission electron microscope.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The TEM requires very thin samples, typically ~100 nanometers or less.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Other techniques, such as ion milling or electropolishing can be used to prepare such thin samples.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] However, the nanometer-scale resolution of the FIB allows the exact region of interest to be chosen, such as perhaps a grain boundary or defect in a material.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] This is vital, for example, in integrated circuit failure analysis.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] If a particular transistor out of several million on a chip is bad, the only tool capable of preparing an electron microscope sample of that single transistor is the FIB.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The same protocol used for preparing samples to transmission electron microscopy can also be used to select a micro area of a sample, extract it and prepare it for analysis using secondary ion mass spectrometry (SIMS).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The drawbacks to FIB sample preparation are the above-mentioned surface damage and implantation, which produce noticeable effects when using techniques such as high-resolution "lattice imaging" TEM or electron energy loss spectroscopy.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] This damaged layer can be minimized by FIB milling with lower beam voltages, or by further milling with a low-voltage argon ion beam after completion of the FIB process.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] FIB preparation can be used with cryogenically frozen samples in a suitably equipped instrument, allowing cross sectional analysis of samples containing liquids or fats, such as biological samples, pharmaceuticals, foams, inks, and food products.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] FIB is also used for secondary ion mass spectrometry (SIMS).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The ejected secondary ions are collected and analyzed after the surface of the specimen has been sputtered with a primary focused ion beam.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The main advantages of this method include a significant reduction of sample preparation time (quick welding and cutting of nanowire at low beam current), and minimization of stress-induced bending, Pt contamination, and ion beam damage.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] This technique is particularly suitable for in situ electron microscopy sample preparation.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The same successive milling steps applied when making TEM samples can be applied to make conical samples for atom probe tomography.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] In this case the ion moved in an annular milling pattern with the inner milling circle being made progressively smaller.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The beam current is generally reduced the smaller the inner circle becomes to avoid damaging or destroying the sample.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The focused ion beam has become a powerful tool for site-specific 3D imaging of sub-micron features in a sample.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] In this FIB tomography technique, the sample is sequentially milled using an ion beam perpendicular to the specimen while imaging the newly exposed surface using an electron beam.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] This so-called "slice and view" approach allows larger scale nano-structures to be characterized across the many imaging modes available to an SEM, including secondary electron, backscattered electron, and energy dispersive x-ray measurement.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The process is destructive, since the specimen is being sequentially milled away after each image is collected.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The collected series of images is then reconstructed to a 3D volume by registering the image stack and removing artifacts.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The predominant artifact that degrades FIB-SEM is ion mill curtaining, where mill patterns form large aperiodic stripes in each image.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The ion mill curtaining can be removed using destriping algorithms.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] FIB-SEM can be done at both room and cryo temperatures as well as on both materials and biological samples.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] It is one of several approaches in Volumetric Electron Microscopy.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Another ion source seen in commercially available instruments is a helium ion source, which is inherently less damaging to the sample than Ga ions although it will still sputter small amounts of material especially at high magnifications and long scan times.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] As helium ions can be focused into a small probe size and provide a much smaller sample interaction than high energy (>1 kV) electrons in the SEM, the He ion microscope can generate equal or higher resolution images with good material contrast and a higher depth of focus.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Commercial instruments are capable of sub 1 nm resolution.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Imaging and milling with Ga ions always result in Ga incorporation near the sample surface.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] As the sample surface is sputtered away at a rate proportional to the sputtering yield and the ion flux (ions per area per time), the Ga is implanted further into the sample, and a steady-state profile of Ga is reached.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] This implantation is often a problem in the range of the semiconductor where silicon can be amorphised by the gallium.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] In order to get an alternative solution to Ga LMI sources, mass-filtered columns have been developed, based on a Wien filter technology.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Such sources include Au-Si, Au-Ge and Au-Si-Ge sources providing Si, Cr, Fe, Co, Ni, Ge, In, Sn, Au, Pb and other elements.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The principle of a Wien filter is based on the equilibrium of the opposite forces induced by perpendicular electrostatic and a magnetic fields acting on accelerated particles.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The proper mass trajectory remains straight and passes through the mass selection aperture while the other masses are stopped.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Besides allowing the use of sources others than gallium, these columns can switch from different species simply by adjusting the properties of the Wien filter.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Larger ions can be used to make rapid milling before refining the contours with smaller ones.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Users also benefit from the possibility to dope their samples with elements of suitable alloy sources.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] The latter property has found great interests in the investigation of magnetic materials and devices.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Khizroev and Litvinov have shown, with the help of magnetic force microscopy (MFM), that there is a critical dose of ions that a magnetic material can be exposed to without experiencing a change in the magnetic properties.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/focused-ion-beam] Exploiting FIB from such an unconventional perspective is especially favourable today when the future of so many novel technologies depends on the ability to rapidly fabricate prototype nanoscale magnetic devices.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] A **scanning electron microscope** (**SEM**) is a type of electron microscope that produces images of a sample by scanning the surface with a focused beam of electrons.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The electrons interact with atoms in the sample, producing various signals that contain information about the surface topography and composition.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The electron beam is scanned in a raster scan pattern, and the position of the beam is combined with the intensity of the detected signal to produce an image.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] In the most common SEM mode, secondary electrons emitted by atoms excited by the electron beam are detected using a secondary electron detector (Everhart–Thornley detector).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The number of secondary electrons that can be detected, and thus the signal intensity, depends, among other things, on specimen topography.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Some SEMs can achieve resolutions better than 1 nanometer.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Specimens are observed in high vacuum in a conventional SEM, or in low vacuum or wet conditions in a variable pressure or environmental SEM, and at a wide range of cryogenic or elevated temperatures with specialized instruments.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] An account of the early history of scanning electron microscopy has been presented by McMullan.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Hall also completed the construction of the first emission microscope in North America, just two years after being tasked by his supervisor, E.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Ardenne applied scanning of the electron beam in an attempt to surpass the resolution of the transmission electron microscope (TEM), as well as to mitigate substantial problems with chromatic aberration inherent to real imaging in the TEM.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] He further discussed the various detection modes, possibilities and theory of SEM, together with the construction of the first high resolution SEM.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The signals used by an SEM to make an image result from interactions between the electron beam and atoms at various depths within the sample.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Various types of signals are produced including secondary electrons (SE), reflected or back-scattered electrons (BSE), characteristic X-rays and light (cathodoluminescence) (CL), absorbed current (specimen current) and transmitted electrons.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Secondary electron imaging and back-scattered electron detectors are standard approaches in an SEM, but additional detectors may be used to capture additional signals.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] For instance, emitted X-rays can be detected by energy dispersive X-ray spectrometry.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Secondary electrons have very low energies on the order of 50 eV, which limits their mean free path in solid matter.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Consequently, SEs can only escape from the top few nanometers of the surface of a sample.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The signal from secondary electrons tends to be highly localized at the point of impact of the primary electron beam, making it possible to collect images of the sample surface with a resolution of below 1 nm.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Back-scattered electrons (BSE) are beam electrons that are reflected from the sample by elastic scattering.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Since they have much higher energy than SEs, they emerge from deeper locations within the specimen and, consequently, the resolution of BSE images is less than SE images.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] However, BSE are often used in analytical SEM, along with the spectra made from the characteristic X-rays, because the intensity of the BSE signal is strongly related to the atomic number (Z) of the specimen.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] BSE images can provide information about the distribution, but not the identity, of different elements in the sample.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] In samples predominantly composed of light elements, such as biological specimens, BSE imaging can image colloidal gold immuno-labels of 5 or 10 nm diameter, which would otherwise be difficult or impossible to detect in secondary electron images.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Characteristic X-rays are emitted when the electron beam removes an inner shell electron from the sample, causing a higher-energy electron to fill the shell and release energy.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The energy or wavelength of these characteristic X-rays can be measured by Energy-dispersive X-ray spectroscopy or Wavelength-dispersive X-ray spectroscopy and used to identify and measure the abundance of elements in the sample and map their distribution.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Due to the very narrow electron beam, SEM micrographs have a large depth of field yielding a characteristic three-dimensional appearance useful for understanding the surface structure of a sample.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] This is exemplified by the micrograph of pollen shown above.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] A wide range of magnifications is possible, from about 10 times (about equivalent to that of a powerful hand-lens) to more than 500,000 times, about 250 times the magnification limit of the best light microscopes.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] SEM samples have to be small enough to fit on the sample stage, secured with a conductive paint.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The relatively low vacuum (0.076 to 20 torr) of Variable-Pressure and Environmental SEM obviates the need for cleaning, even those with water or oily films, allowing observation in a natural state.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Preparation is identical to the steps used in light microscopy polished samples.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] SEM techniques can be used to examine integrated circuit condition and attachment points.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Foreshortening is achieved by tilting any specimen.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Sputter coating is used to apply a thin coating of metal, or metal alloy, to nonconductive specimens.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Conductive materials in current use for specimen coating include gold, gold/palladium alloy, platinum, iridium, tungsten, chromium, osmium..
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] An alternative to coating for some biological samples is to increase the bulk conductivity of the material by impregnation with osmium using variants of the OTO staining method (O-osmium tetroxide, T-thiocarbohydrazide, O-osmium).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Since the SEM specimen chamber is under high vacuum, a SEM specimen must be completely dry or cryogenically cooled.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Hard, dry materials such as wood, bone, feathers, dried insects, or shells (including egg shells) can be examined with little further treatment, but living cells and tissues and whole, soft-bodied organisms require chemical fixation to preserve and stabilize their structure.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Fixation is usually performed by incubation in a solution of a buffered chemical fixative, such as glutaraldehyde, sometimes in combination with formaldehyde and other fixatives, and optionally followed by postfixation with osmium tetroxide.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Because air-drying causes collapse and shrinkage, this is commonly achieved by replacement of water in the cells with organic solvents such as ethanol or acetone, and replacement of these solvents in turn with a transitional fluid such as liquid carbon dioxide by critical point drying.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The carbon dioxide is finally removed while in a supercritical state, so that no gas–liquid interface is present within the sample during drying.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The dry specimen is usually mounted on a specimen stub using an adhesive such as epoxy resin or electrically conductive double-sided adhesive tape, and sputter-coated with gold or gold/palladium alloy before examination in the microscope.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Samples may be sectioned (with a microtome) if information about the organism's internal ultrastructure is to be exposed for imaging.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] If the SEM is equipped with a cold stage for cryo microscopy, cryofixation may be used and low-temperature scanning electron microscopy performed on the cryogenically fixed specimens.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Cryo-fixed specimens may be cryo-fractured under vacuum in a special apparatus to reveal internal structure, sputter-coated and transferred onto the SEM cryo-stage while still frozen.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Low-temperature scanning electron microscopy (LT-SEM) is also applicable to the imaging of temperature-sensitive materials such as ice and fats.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Freeze-fracturing, freeze-etch or freeze-and-break is a preparation method particularly useful for examining lipid membranes and their incorporated proteins in "face on" view.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The preparation method reveals the proteins embedded in the lipid bilayer.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] According to Goldstein et al, "There are many ways to section the samples, including blade sawing, wire sawing, abrasive cutting, fracturing (best for more brittle materials), shearing, spark erosion, and microtomy.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The surface to be prepared for microstructural analysis is polished using a graded sequence of abrasive materials.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] For elements with atomic numbers 8 through 20, only carbon, aluminum and chromium are suitable coating materials.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] FIB is analogous to SEM, but with the use of positively charged ions instead of electrons.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Besides imaging, FIB can be used for precision cutting, etching, or depositing conductive materials on the sample surface.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The SEM consists of an electron column, with the electron gun, electron lenses and vacuum pumps, plus a control console, with viewing screen and electron beam controls.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The electron gun generates and accelerates electrons between 0.1 to 30 keV.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Electron lenses focus the electron beam to less than 10 nm at the sample, where it interacts with the specimen to a depth of about 1 micrometre, generating signals used for point by point imaging.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Deflection coils sweep the electron beam across the specimen in a raster scan fashion, with the backscattered and secondary electrons collected by the electron detector, forming an image that can be processed and displayed digitally.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Sharpness and feature visibility are controlled by electron probe size, electron probe current, electron probe convergence angle and electron beam accelerating voltage.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Magnification in an SEM can be controlled over a range of about 6 orders of magnitude from about 10 to 3,000,000 times.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Changing magnification is achieved by adjusting the length of the scan on the specimen, with higher magnification requiring a smaller sample area, or pixel.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The most common imaging mode collects low-energy (<50 eV) secondary electrons that are ejected from conduction or valence bands of the specimen atoms by inelastic scattering interactions with beam electrons.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Due to their low energy, these electrons originate from within a few nanometers below the sample surface.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The electrons are detected by an Everhart–Thornley detector.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Backscattered electrons (BSE) consist of high-energy electrons originating in the electron beam, that are reflected or back-scattered out of the specimen interaction volume by elastic scattering interactions with specimen atoms.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Since heavy elements (high atomic number) backscatter electrons more strongly than light elements (low atomic number), and thus appear brighter in the image, BSEs are used to detect contrast between areas with different chemical compositions.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] According to Goldstein et al, "When the E-T detector is biased negatively, only backscattered electrons are detected.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] All secondary electrons are rejected, including those that are emitted from the specimen in the direction of the E-T detector within the line-of-sight solid angle for direct geometric collection.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Dedicated backscattered electron detectors are designed to greatly increase the solid angle of collection." These include the Passive Scintillator Backscattered Electron Detectors, the Backscattered-to-Secondary Electron Conversion Detector, and the Solid State Diode Detector.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Backscattered electrons can also be used to form an electron backscatter diffraction (EBSD) image that can be used to determine the crystallographic structure of the specimen.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Voltage contrast and charge collection SEM microscopy are used to characterize the electrical performance of integrated circuits and semiconductor devices.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Charge collection uses the currents or voltages induced in the specimen by the electron beam.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Electron beam induced current (EBIC) is used to study Schottky barriers, diffused, and ion-implanted p-n junctions.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Cathodoluminescence can be used to detect impurities in minerals, or the persence of excess electron-hole pairs in semiconductors..
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Cathodoluminescence, the emission of light when atoms excited by high-energy electrons return to their ground state, is analogous to UV-induced fluorescence, and some materials such as zinc sulfide and some fluorescent dyes, exhibit both phenomena.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Over the last decades, cathodoluminescence was most commonly experienced as the light emission from the inner surface of the cathode-ray tube in television sets and computer CRT monitors.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] In the SEM, CL detectors either collect all light emitted by the specimen or can analyse the wavelengths emitted by the specimen and display an emission spectrum or an image of the distribution of cathodoluminescence emitted by the specimen in real color.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Characteristic X-rays that are produced by the interaction of electrons with the sample may also be detected in an SEM equipped for energy-dispersive X-ray spectroscopy or wavelength dispersive X-ray spectroscopy.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Analysis of the x-ray signals may be used to map the distribution and estimate the abundance of elements in the sample.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Many SEM-based research studies are supported by complementary nanoscale techniques such as atomic force microscopy (AFM) and its electrical imaging modes.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] These methods provide insights that go beyond surface morphology.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] For example, AFM can probe the sample's surface topography at the nanometer scale using a sharp tip in contact or tapping mode.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Conductive AFM (C-AFM) enables mapping of local electrical conductivity, useful in studying resistive switching materials and semiconductors.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Kelvin probe force microscopy (KPFM) measures surface potential variations, which is valuable for analyzing charge distributions in electronic or photovoltaic materials.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] When used alongside SEM, these techniques offer a comprehensive understanding of both structural and functional properties of materials.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] A SEM is not a camera and the detector is not continuously image-forming like a CCD array or film.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Unlike in an optical system, the resolution is not limited by the diffraction limit, fineness of lenses or mirrors or detector array resolution.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The focusing optics can be large and coarse, and the SE detector is fist-sized and simply detects current.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Instead, the spatial resolution of the SEM depends on the size of the electron spot, which in turn depends on both the wavelength of the electrons and the electron-optical system that produces the scanning beam.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The resolution is also limited by the size of the interaction volume, the volume of specimen material that interacts with the electron beam.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The spot size and the interaction volume are both large compared to the distances between atoms, so the resolution of the SEM is not high enough to image individual atoms, as is possible with a transmission electron microscope (TEM).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The SEM has compensating advantages, though, including the ability to image a comparatively large area of the specimen; the ability to image bulk materials (not just thin films or foils); and the variety of analytical modes available for measuring the composition and properties of the specimen.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Depending on the instrument, the resolution can fall somewhere between less than 1 nm and 20 nm.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] As of 2009, The world's highest resolution conventional (≤30 kV) SEM can reach a point resolution of 0.4 nm using a secondary electron detector.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Conventional SEM requires samples to be imaged under vacuum, because a gas atmosphere rapidly spreads and attenuates electron beams.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] As a consequence, samples that produce a significant amount of vapour, e.g. wet biological samples or oil-bearing rock, must be either dried or cryogenically frozen.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Processes involving phase transitions, such as the drying of adhesives or melting of alloys, liquid transport, chemical reactions, and solid-air-gas systems, in general cannot be observed with conventional high-vacuum SEM.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] In environmental SEM (ESEM), the chamber is evacuated of air, but water vapor is retained near its saturation pressure, and the residual pressure remains relatively high.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] This allows the analysis of samples containing water or other volatile substances.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] With ESEM, observations of living insects have been possible.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The first commercial development of the ESEM in the late 1980s allowed samples to be observed in low-pressure gaseous environments (e.g.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The first commercial ESEMs were produced by the ElectroScan Corporation in USA in 1988.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] ElectroScan was taken over by Philips (who later sold their electron-optics division to FEI Company) in 1996.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] ESEM is especially useful for non-metallic and biological materials because coating with carbon or gold is unnecessary.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Uncoated plastics and elastomers can be routinely examined, as can uncoated biological samples.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] This is useful because coating can be difficult to reverse, may conceal small features on the surface of the sample and may reduce the value of the results obtained.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] X-ray analysis is difficult with a coating of a heavy metal, so carbon coatings are routinely used in conventional SEMs, but ESEM makes it possible to perform X-ray microanalysis on uncoated non-conductive specimens; however some specific for ESEM artifacts are introduced in X-ray analysis.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] ESEM may be the preferred for electron microscopy of unique samples from criminal or civil actions, where forensic analysis may need to be repeated by several different experts.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] It is possible to study specimens in liquid with ESEM or with other liquid-phase electron microscopy methods.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The SEM can also be used in transmission mode by incorporating an appropriate detector below a thin specimen section.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Detectors are available for bright field, dark field, as well as segmented detectors for mid-field to high angle annular dark-field.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Despite the difference in instrumentation, this technique is still commonly referred to as scanning transmission electron microscopy (STEM).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Since 2016, there has been growing interest in the use of transmission-mode SEM for Electron Energy Loss Spectroscopy (EELS).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Pioneered by Hitachi and the Gauvin group at McGill University, SEM-EELS elemental mapping of thin specimens is now possible, along with reduced beam damage in lithiated materials due to the lower beam energy reducing knock-on damage.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] In 2025, scientists from MIT demonstrated that EELS analysis of thin specimens is possible in any retrofitted SEM in the 1-20 keV energy range.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The SEM is used often in Forensic Science for magnified analysis of microscopic things such as diatoms and gunshot residue.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Because SEM is a nondestructive force on the sample, it can be used to analyze evidence without damaging it.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The SEM shoots a beam of high energy electrons to the sample which bounce off of the sample without changing or destroying it.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] This is great when it comes to analyzing diatoms.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] When a person dies by drowning, they inhale the water which causes what is in the water (diatoms) to get in the blood stream, brain, kidneys, and more.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] These diatoms in the body can be magnified with the SEM to determine the type of diatoms which aid in understanding how and where the person died.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] By using the images produced by the SEM, forensic scientists can compare diatoms types to confirm the body of water a person died in.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] GSR can be collected from the crime scene, victim, or shooter and analyzed with the SEM.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] This can help scientists determine proximity and or contact with the discharged firearm.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Electron microscopes do not naturally produce color images.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] A secondary electron detector produces a single value per pixel that corresponds to the number of electrons received by the detector during the short period of time when the beam is targeted to the (x, y) pixel position.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] For each pixel, this single value is represented by a grey level, forming a monochrome image.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] However, several methods can used to get color electron microscopy images.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The easiest way to get color is to replace each grey level with an arbitrary color, using a color look-up table.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] This method is known as false color imaging and can help to distinguish phases of the sample with similar properties or composition.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] As an alternative to simply replacing each grey level by a color, a sample observed by an oblique beam allows researchers to create an approximative topography image (see further section "Photometric 3D rendering from a single SEM image").
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Such topography can then be processed by 3D-rendering algorithms for a more natural rendering of the surface texture.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Very often, published SEM images are artificially colored.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] This may be done for aesthetic effect, to clarify structure or to add a realistic appearance to the sample and generally does not add information about the specimen.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Coloring may be performed manually with photo-editing software, or semi-automatically with dedicated software using feature-detection or object-oriented segmentation.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Alternately, when additional information from other detectors like EDX, EBSD, ECCI or cathodoluminescence is available, it can be merged as color channel(s) to provide rich material information in a single, high-resolution image.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] In some configurations more information is gathered per pixel, often by the use of multiple detectors.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] As a common example, secondary electron and backscattered electron detectors are superimposed and a color is assigned to each of the images captured by each detector, with a result of a combined color image where colors are related to the density of the components.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] This method is known as density-dependent color SEM (DDC-SEM).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Micrographs produced by DDC-SEM retain topographical information, which is better captured by the secondary electrons detector and combine it to the information about density, obtained by the backscattered electron detector.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Measurement of the energy of photons emitted from the specimen is a common method to get analytical capabilities.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Examples are the energy-dispersive X-ray spectroscopy (EDS) detectors used in elemental analysis and cathodoluminescence microscope (CL) systems that analyse the intensity and spectrum of electron-induced luminescence in (for example) geological specimens.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] In SEM systems using these detectors it is common to color code these extra signals and superimpose them in a single color image, so that differences in the distribution of the various components of the specimen can be seen clearly and compared.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Optionally, the standard secondary electron image can be merged with the one or more compositional channels, so that the specimen's structure and composition can be compared.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Such images can be made while maintaining the full integrity of the original signal data, which is not modified in any way.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Unlike SPMs, SEMs do not naturally produce 3D images.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] However 3D data can be obtained using an SEM by methods such as Stereoscopy.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] This method typically uses a four-quadrant BSE detector (alternatively for one manufacturer, a 3-segment detector).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The microscope produces four images of the same specimen at the same time, so no tilt of the sample is required.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The method gives metrological 3D dimensions as far as the slope of the specimen remains reasonable.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Most SEM manufacturers now (2018) offer such a built-in or optional four-quadrant BSE detector, together with proprietary software to calculate a 3D image in real time.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Other approaches use more sophisticated (and sometimes GPU-intensive) methods like the optimal estimation algorithm and offer much better results at the cost of high demands on computing power.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] In all instances, this approach works by integration of the slope, so vertical slopes and overhangs are ignored; for instance, if an entire sphere lies on a flat, little more than the upper hemisphere is seen emerging above the flat, resulting in wrong altitude of the sphere apex.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The prominence of this effect depends on the angle of the BSE detectors with respect to the sample, but these detectors are usually situated around (and close to) the electron beam, so this effect is very common.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] This method requires an SEM image obtained in oblique low angle lighting.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The grey-level is then interpreted as the slope, and the slope integrated to restore the specimen topography.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] This method is interesting for visual enhancement and the detection of the shape and position of objects; however the vertical heights cannot usually be calibrated, contrary to other methods such as photogrammetry.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] One possible application is measuring the roughness of ice crystals.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] This method can combine variable-pressure environmental SEM and the 3D capabilities of the SEM to measure roughness on individual ice crystal facets, convert it into a computer model and run further statistical analysis on the model.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Other measurements include fractal dimension, examining fracture surface of metals, characterization of materials, corrosion measurement, and dimensional measurements at the nano scale (step height, volume, angle, flatness, bearing ratio, coplanarity, etc.).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] SEM is also used by art conservationists to discern threats to paintings' surface stability due to aging, such as the formations of complexes of zinc ions with fatty acids.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] Forensic scientists use SEM to detect art forgeries.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/scanning-electron-microscope] The following are examples of images taken using an SEM.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/secondary-electrons] Secondary electrons are also the main means of viewing images in the scanning electron microscope (SEM).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/secondary-electrons] The range of secondary electrons depends on the energy.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/secondary-electrons] Plotting the inelastic mean free path as a function of energy often shows characteristics of the "universal curve" familiar to electron spectroscopists and surface analysts.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/secondary-electrons] This distance is on the order of a few nanometers in metals and tens of nanometers in insulators.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/secondary-electrons] This small distance allows such fine resolution to be achieved in the SEM.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/secondary-electrons] For SiO2, for a primary electron energy of 100 eV, the secondary electron range is up to 20 nm from the point of incidence.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] In transmission electron microscope, a thin crystalline sample is illuminated by parallel beam of electrons accelerated to energy of hundreds of kiloelectron volts.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] At these energies samples are transparent for the electrons if the sample is thinned enough (typically less than 100 nm).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] Due to the wave–particle duality, the high-energetic electrons behave as matter waves with wavelength of a few thousandths of a nanometer.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] where h is the Planck constant, $m_{0}$ is the electron rest mass, e is the elementary charge, c is the speed of light and V is an electric potential accelerating the electrons (also called acceleration voltage).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] For instance the acceleration voltage of 200 kV results in a wavelength of 2.508 pm.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] Since the spacing between atoms in crystals is about a hundred times larger, the electrons are diffracted on the crystal lattice, acting as a diffraction grating.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] Due to the diffraction, part of the electrons is scattered at particular angles (diffracted beams), while others pass through the sample without changing their direction (transmitted beams).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] In order to determine the diffraction angles, the electron beam normally incident to the atomic lattice can be seen as a planar wave, which is re-transmitted by each atom as a spherical wave.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] where the integer n is an order of diffraction and d is the distance between atoms (if only one row of atoms is assumed as in the illustration aside) or a distance between atomic planes parallel to the beam (in a real 3D atomic structure).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] For finite samples this equation is only approximately correct.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] After being deflected by the microscope's magnetic lens, each set of initially parallel beams intersect in the back focal plane forming the diffraction pattern.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] The transmitted beams intersect right in the optical axis.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] The diffracted beams intersect at certain distance from the optical axis (corresponding to interplanar distance of the planes diffracting the beams) and under certain azimuth (corresponding to the orientation of the planes diffracting the beams).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] This allows to form a pattern of bright spots typical for SAD.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] SAD is called "selected" because it allows the user to select the sample area from which the diffraction pattern will be acquired.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] For this purpose, there is a selected area aperture located below the sample holder.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] It is a metallic sheet with several differently sized holes which can be inserted into the beam.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] The user can select the aperture of appropriate size and position it so that it only allows to pass the portion of beam corresponding to the selected area.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] Therefore, the resulting diffraction pattern will only reflect the area selected by the aperture.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] This allows to study small objects such as crystallites in polycrystalline material with a broad parallel beam.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] Character of the resulting diffraction image depends on whether the beam is diffracted by one single crystal or by number of differently oriented crystallites for instance in a polycrystalline material.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] The single-crystalline diffractogram depicts a regular pattern of bright spots.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] This pattern can be seen as a two-dimensional projection of reciprocal crystal lattice.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] If there are more contributing crystallites, the diffraction image becomes a superposition of individual crystals' diffraction patterns.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] Ultimately, this superposition contains diffraction spots of all possible crystallographic plane systems in all possible orientations.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] There are all possible orientations of crystallographic planes and therefore the diffraction spots are formed around the transmitted beam in the whole 360-degree azimuthal range.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] SAD analysis is widely used in material research for its relative simplicity and high information value.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] Once the sample is prepared and examined in a modern transmission electron microscope, the device allows for a routine diffraction acquisition in a matter of seconds.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] If the images are interpreted correctly, they can be used to identify crystal structures, determine their orientations, measure crystal characteristics, examine crystal defects or material textures.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] The course of analysis depends on whether the diffractogram depicts ring or spot diffraction pattern and on the quantity to be determined.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] Software tools based on computer vision algorithms simplifies quantitative analysis.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] If the SAD is taken from one a or a few single crystals, the diffractogram depicts a regular pattern of bright spots.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] Since the diffraction pattern can be seen as a two-dimensional projection of reciprocal crystal lattice, the pattern can be used to measure lattice constants, specifically the distances and angles between crystallographic planes.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] The lattice parameters are typically distinctive for various materials and their phases which allows to identify the examined material or at least differentiate between possible candidates.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] Even though the SAD-based analyses were not considered quantitative for a long time, computer tools brought accuracy and repeatability allowing to routinely perform accurate measurements of interplanar distances or angles on appropriately calibrated microscopes.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] Tools such as CrysTBox are capable of automated analysis achieving sub-pixel precision.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] If the sample is tilted against the electron beam, diffraction conditions are satisfied for different set of crystallographic planes yielding different constellation of diffraction spots.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] This allows to determine the crystal orientation, which can be used for instance to set up the orientation needed for particular experiment, to determine misorientation between adjacent grains or crystal twins.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] Since different sample orientations provide different projections of the reciprocal lattice, they provide an opportunity to reconstruct the three-dimensional information lost in individual projections.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] A series of diffractograms varying in tilt can be acquired and processed with diffraction tomography analysis in order to reconstruct an unknown crystal structure.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] SAD can also be used to analyze crystal defects such as stacking faults.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] as recorded (left) and processed with CrysTBox ringGUI (right).
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] If the illuminated area selected by the aperture covers many differently oriented crystallites, their diffraction patterns superimpose forming an image of concentric rings.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] The ring diffractogram is typical for polycrystalline samples, powders or nanoparticles.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] Diameter of each ring corresponds to interplanar distance of a plane system present in the sample.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] Instead of information about individual grains or the sample orientation, this diffractogram provides more of a statistical information for instance about overall crystallinity or texture.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] Textured materials are characteristic by a non-uniform intensity distribution along the ring circumference despite crystallinity sufficient for generating smooth rings.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] Ring diffractograms can be also used to discriminate between nanocrystalline and amorphous phases.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] Not all the features depicted in the diffraction image are necessarily wanted.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] The transmitted beam is often too strong and needs to be shadowed with a beam-stopper in order to protect the camera.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] The beam-stopper typically shadows part of the useful information as well.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] Towards the rings center, the background intensity also gradually increases lowering the contrast of diffraction rings.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] Modern analytical software allows to minimize such unwanted image features and together with other functionalities improves the image readability it helps with image interpretation.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] An SADP is acquired under parallel electron illumination.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] In the case of convergent beam, a convergent beam electron diffraction (CBED) is achieved.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] The beam used in SAD is broad illuminating a wide sample area.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] In order to analyze only a specific sample area, the selected area aperture in the image plane is used.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] This is in contrast with nanodiffraction, where the site-selectivity is achieved using a beam condensed to a narrow probe.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] SAD is important in direct imaging for instance when orienting the sample for high resolution microscopy or setting up dark-field imaging conditions.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] High-resolution electron microscope images can be transformed into an artificial diffraction pattern using Fourier transform.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] Then, they can be processed the same way as real diffractograms allowing to determine crystal orientation, measure interplanar angles and distances even with picometric precision.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] SAD is similar to X-ray diffraction, but unique in that areas as small as several hundred nanometres in size can be examined, whereas X-ray diffraction typically samples areas much larger.
[src:electron-microscopy-materials/selected-area-diffraction] It is also similar to low-energy electron diffraction (LEED), though this uses back-scattered rather than transmitted electrons and at low energies, therefore being much more surface-sensitive.
